42nd lvl Medding Machine <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/ustad6.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Stad6</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Apprentice</span><br> <font color=#ffffff>(7/3/01 7:54:11 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Just learned quadding...  OMG</span><hr size=1> Yup.  Quadding is such a wonderful thing.  I'm currently doing that in Overthere on Sarnak Knights, Spiky Succulents and Stonegazer Cocatrices.  I tend to avoid rhinos and tigers as their running speed is troublesome when it comes to snaring them.  My little system goes something like this.<br>
<br>
I bind at a known safe point away from my &quot;moment of truth spot&quot; (explained a little later).  For instance, I'm currently bound between the gargoyle guards at the Overthere outpost.  First, I go round up any combination of the knights, spikys and gazers.  I drag them over to the &quot;moment of truth spot&quot; on the western wall north of the Skyfire zoneline and then try to snare them.  This is consistently my spot where I do this action.  <br>
<br>
If the snare is resisted by one or more of the mobs, I can gate and camp to clear the hate list without the mobs making it back to damage me.  I can then round up more mobs to try again.  I've found that it gets cumbersome to try to snare a resister, round them up again and resnare.  It is just easier to completely start over and costs less mana to do so.  Once the snare takes on the entire lot, it is all downhill from there.  Currently, I'm getting anywhere between 1 1/4 to 2 blue bubbles per kite, which is not too shabby.<br>
<br>
My two coppers is that the staff of temperate flux is quite handy for this.  Firstly, the staff is excellent to pull with.  I hit each mob with the flux 10 times or so and that pretty much guarantees they will fix their attention on me for the duration of the chase.  Secondly, the staff is important to gauge distance on the initial snare.  Since the mobs are running at full speed, it is handy to start the cast exactly when they come into range.  This helps so that if one resists, you still have time to run from the resister.  <br>
<br>
I always keep steelskin running doing this.  Internet latency will sometimes do unusual things, and you'll get hit when you otherwise wouldn't expect.  It's saved my bacon more than a few times.<br>
